Calibration plots for Fe3+ in pH 4.0, λex = 370 nm, λem = 472 nm, at 25 °C are depicted in Fig. 3
                           . Where the detection limit (DL
                            = 3σ/slope) and quantitation limit (QL
                            = 10 σ/slope) for sensing of Fe3+ ions via AAP sensor estimated to be 1.59 nmol L−1 and 5.31 nmol L−1, respectively with a good linearity of Fe(III) concentration is found from 2 nmol L−1 to 0.4 μmol L-1 (Table 2
                           ). This limit of detection is 160 times lower than the limit value (≈ 5.5 M) allowed by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency in drinkable water [44] also it was lower than those for previously reported methods [45–54] (Table 3
                           ).

The selectivity of AAP sensor against different interfering cations has been investigated in the absence of Fe3+ ions (Fig. 5
                        ). It is obvious that, there is no significant change on the intensity at λem 470 nm after addition of 10 μmol L−1 of interfering cations to AAP sensor as shown in Fig. 6
                        , which confirm the high selectivity towards Fe3+ ions.
